{"title_page": "Mangala Samaraweera", "text_new": "{{short description|Sri Lankan politician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = [[Honourable Member|Hon.]]\n| name = Mangala Samaraweera\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0db8\u0d82\u0d9c\u0dbd \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd3\u0dbb \u0dc3\u0db8\u0db1\u0dbd\u0dba\u0dcf}}\n| image = Mangala Samaraweera.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office1 = [[Minister of Finance (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Finance]]\n| term_start1 = 22 May 2017\n| term_end1 = 17 November 2019\n| president1 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Ravi Karunanayake]]\n| successor1 = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n| office2 = [[Minister of Media]]\n| term_start2 = 22 May 2017\n| term_end2 = 17 November 2019\n| president2 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Gayantha Karunathilaka]]\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start3 = 12 January 2015\n| term_end3 = 22 May 2017\n| president3 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor3 = [[G. L. Peiris|Gamini L Peiris]]\n| successor3 = [[Ravi Karunanayake]]\n| term_start4 = 23 November 2005\n| term_end4 = 28 January 2007\n| president4 = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Ratnasiri Wickremanayake]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Anura Bandaranaike]]\n| successor4 = [[Rohitha Bogollagama]]\n| constituency_MP5 = [[Matara Electoral District|Matara District]]\n| parliament5 = Sri Lanka\n| majority5 = \n| term_start5 = 15 February 1989\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| prior_term = \n| birthname = Mangala Pinsiri Samaraweera\n| birth_date = {{Birth_date and age|1956|04|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| restingplace = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| party = [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] <sup>(1983-2007)</sup><br />[[United National Party]] <br /><sup>(2010-present)</sup>\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| parents = [[Mahanama Samaraweera]]<br />(father)<br>Khema Padmawathi Samaraweera(mother)\n| blank1 = Ethnicity\n}}\n\n'''Mangala Pinsiri Samaraweera''' ({{lang-si| \u0db8\u0d82\u0d9c\u0dbd \u0db4\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dd2 \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd3\u0dbb \u0dc3\u0db8\u0db1\u0dbd\u0dba\u0dcf}}, {{lang-ta|\u0bae\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3 \u0b9a\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bb5\u0bc0\u0bb0}}; {{IPA-si|m\u02c8\u028c\u014bg\u0258l\u0258 pinsiri s\u02c8\u028cm\u0258r\u0258vi\u02d0r\u0258|pron}}; born 21 April 1956), better known as '''Mangala Samaraweera''', is an MP of UNP party [[Sri Lanka]] and former [[Minister of Finance]] and Media, appointed 2017. He previously held that post of Foreign Minister two terms from 2005 to 2007 and 2015 to 2017. He created a stir in Sri Lankan politics when he was sacked as a minister by President [[Mahinda Rajapakse]] in 2007, after which he formed a new political party called the Sri Lanka Freedom Party (Mahajana) Wing which merged into the [[United National Party]] in 2010.<ref>''Daily Mirror'', [http://www.dailymirror.lk/2007/06/27/front/03.asp SLFP (M) unveils \u2018policy\u2019]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMangala Samaraweera is the son of [[Mahanama Samaraweera]], who was a Cabinet Minister of Local Government, Housing,Communications,Posts and Telecommunications  in [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]'s government, and Khema Samaraweera, a member of the Matara Urban Council. A graduate in Clothing Design and Technology from [[St. Martin's School of Art]] in [[London]], he served as a design consultant to the National Design Center of Sri Lanka prior to his political career.\n\nHe is openly gay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/standing-up-for-the-gay-politician-mangala-samaraweera-on-right-track/|title=Standing Up For The Gay Politician: Mangala Samaraweera On Right Track?|date=2017-05-08|work=Colombo Telegraph|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref> In November 2018, After homophobic comments made by President [[Maithripala Sirisena]], He wrote on Twitter that \u201cI would rather be a butterfly than a leech Mr. President!!!\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Better-butterfly-than-a-leech--Mangala-to-Sirisena/44-666227|title=Better butterfly than a leech: Mangala to Sirisena {{!}} FT Online|website=www.ft.lk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nHe was the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]]'s chief organizer for the southern city [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]] beginning in 1983 and Assistant Secretary of the SLFP Coordinating Secretary of the Mother\u2019s Front.\n\nHe first entered the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka]] as a representative of the Matara District in 1989, and he was appointed as Minister of Post & Telecommunications in the cabinet of President [[Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga]] in 1994. He also served as the Minister of Urban Development, Construction and Public Utilities in the same Cabinet after a reshuffle and was later given the Deputy Minister of Finance portfolio.\n\nFollowing the election defeat of his party in 2001, he was made the Chief Opposition Whip and the Treasurer of the SLFP. In 2004 he became the Minister of Ports, Aviation and Media in the new cabinet of President [[Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga]].\n\nIn June 2005, after conflicts with Kumaratunga, he dropped the Media Ministry, but remained Cabinet Minister of Ports and Aviation. He became the campaign manager for Presidential candidate and Prime Minister [[Mahinda Rajapakse]]. When Rajapakse won and took office in November 2005, he surprised many by appointing Samaraweera to the additional post of [[Minister of Foreign Affairs of Sri Lanka|Foreign Minister]] instead of Prime Minister; Samaraweera maintained his other posts.\n\nIn late January 2007, Samaraweera was replaced as Foreign Minister, but remained as Minister of Ports and Aviation.<ref>[http://english.people.com.cn/200701/29/eng20070129_345575.html \"Sri Lankan president reshuffles cabinet\"], Xinhua, January 29, 2007.</ref> On 9 February 2007, he was sacked from the cabinet together with ministers [[Anura Bandaranaike]] and [[Sripathi Sooriyarachchi]] after falling out with the president. He then went on to create a new political party, the SLFP (Mahajana) wing.\n\nIn October 2013, the Matara Magistrate's Court issued a Court order to arrest him and 10 others for their alleged involvement in obstructing a peaceful protest march in Matara by UNP activists, to oust its leader [[Ranil Wickramasinghe]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailynews.lk/local/arrest-mangala-orders-court | title=ARREST MANGALA ORDERS COURT | work=Dailymirror.lk | date=15 Oct 2013 | access-date=16 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016233022/http://www.dailynews.lk/local/arrest-mangala-orders-court | archive-date=16 October 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2015 Samaraweera was again appointed as Minister of Foreign Affairs under newly elected President [[Maithripala Sirisena]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Sri-Lankan-foreign-minister-Mangala-Samaraweera-to-visit-India/articleshow/45865923.cms | title=Sri Lankan foreign minister Mangala Samaraweera to visit India | work=The Times of India | date=13 January 2015 | accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n*[[List of political families in Sri Lanka]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091201023812/http://www.mangalasamaraweera.com/  Mangala Samaraweera's Official Website]\n*[http://www.lankadissent.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1315:mangala-for-de    Mangala for democratic leadership in SLFP]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091226091022/http://sri_lanka.comnat.unesco.org/index.php?intIdCat=103&blnIsCat=1&intIdLang=1 UNESCO Executive Board]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100324204136/http://www.parliament.lk/directory_of_members/ViewMember.do?memID=186 Parliament profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[G. L. Peiris|Gamini L Peiris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Foreign Affairs of Sri Lanka]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ravi Karunanayake]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anura Bandaranaike]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Foreign Affairs of Sri Lanka]]|years=2005-2007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rohitha Bogollagama]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan foreign ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan Telecommunications ministers}}\n{{Members of 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Samaraweera, Mangala}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Theravada Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Saint Martin's School of Art]]\n[[Category:People from Matara]]\n[[Category:Housing ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Posts ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Telecommunication ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT legislators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sri Lankan politician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = [[Honourable Member|Hon.]]\n| name = Mangala Samaraweera\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0db8\u0d82\u0d9c\u0dbd \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd3\u0dbb}}\n| image = Mangala Samaraweera.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office1 = [[Minister of Finance (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Finance]]\n| term_start1 = 22 May 2017\n| term_end1 = 17 November 2019\n| president1 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Ravi Karunanayake]]\n| successor1 = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n| office2 = [[Minister of Media]]\n| term_start2 = 22 May 2017\n| term_end2 = 17 November 2019\n| president2 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Gayantha Karunathilaka]]\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start3 = 12 January 2015\n| term_end3 = 22 May 2017\n| president3 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor3 = [[G. L. Peiris|Gamini L Peiris]]\n| successor3 = [[Ravi Karunanayake]]\n| term_start4 = 23 November 2005\n| term_end4 = 28 January 2007\n| president4 = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Ratnasiri Wickremanayake]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Anura Bandaranaike]]\n| successor4 = [[Rohitha Bogollagama]]\n| constituency_MP5 = [[Matara Electoral District|Matara District]]\n| parliament5 = Sri Lanka\n| majority5 = \n| term_start5 = 15 February 1989\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| prior_term = \n| birthname = Mangala Pinsiri Samaraweera\n| birth_date = {{Birth_date and age|1956|04|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| restingplace = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| party = [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] <sup>(1983-2007)</sup><br />[[United National Party]] <br /><sup>(2010-present)</sup>\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| parents = [[Mahanama Samaraweera]]<br />(father)<br>Khema Padmawathi Samaraweera(mother)\n| blank1 = Ethnicity\n}}\n\n'''Mangala Pinsiri Samaraweera''' ({{lang-si| \u0db8\u0d82\u0d9c\u0dbd \u0db4\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dd2 \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd3\u0dbb}}, {{lang-ta|\u0bae\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3 \u0b9a\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bb5\u0bc0\u0bb0}}; {{IPA-si|m\u02c8\u028c\u014bg\u0258l\u0258 pinsiri s\u02c8\u028cm\u0258r\u0258vi\u02d0r\u0258|pron}}; born 21 April 1956), better known as '''Mangala Samaraweera''', is an MP of UNP party [[Sri Lanka]] and former [[Minister of Finance]] and Media, appointed 2017. He previously held that post of Foreign Minister two terms from 2005 to 2007 and 2015 to 2017. He created a stir in Sri Lankan politics when he was sacked as a minister by President [[Mahinda Rajapakse]] in 2007, after which he formed a new political party called the Sri Lanka Freedom Party (Mahajana) Wing which merged into the [[United National Party]] in 2010.<ref>''Daily Mirror'', [http://www.dailymirror.lk/2007/06/27/front/03.asp SLFP (M) unveils \u2018policy\u2019]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMangala Samaraweera is the son of [[Mahanama Samaraweera]], who was a Cabinet Minister of Local Government, Housing,Communications,Posts and Telecommunications  in [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]'s government, and Khema Samaraweera, a member of the Matara Urban Council. A graduate in Clothing Design and Technology from [[St. Martin's School of Art]] in [[London]], he served as a design consultant to the National Design Center of Sri Lanka prior to his political career.\n\nHe is openly gay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/standing-up-for-the-gay-politician-mangala-samaraweera-on-right-track/|title=Standing Up For The Gay Politician: Mangala Samaraweera On Right Track?|date=2017-05-08|work=Colombo Telegraph|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-US}}</ref> In November 2018, After homophobic comments made by President [[Maithripala Sirisena]], He wrote on Twitter that \u201cI would rather be a butterfly than a leech Mr. President!!!\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Better-butterfly-than-a-leech--Mangala-to-Sirisena/44-666227|title=Better butterfly than a leech: Mangala to Sirisena {{!}} FT Online|website=www.ft.lk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nHe was the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]]'s chief organizer for the southern city [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]] beginning in 1983 and Assistant Secretary of the SLFP Coordinating Secretary of the Mother\u2019s Front.\n\nHe first entered the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka]] as a representative of the Matara District in 1989, and he was appointed as Minister of Post & Telecommunications in the cabinet of President [[Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga]] in 1994. He also served as the Minister of Urban Development, Construction and Public Utilities in the same Cabinet after a reshuffle and was later given the Deputy Minister of Finance portfolio.\n\nFollowing the election defeat of his party in 2001, he was made the Chief Opposition Whip and the Treasurer of the SLFP. In 2004 he became the Minister of Ports, Aviation and Media in the new cabinet of President [[Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga]].\n\nIn June 2005, after conflicts with Kumaratunga, he dropped the Media Ministry, but remained Cabinet Minister of Ports and Aviation. He became the campaign manager for Presidential candidate and Prime Minister [[Mahinda Rajapakse]]. When Rajapakse won and took office in November 2005, he surprised many by appointing Samaraweera to the additional post of [[Minister of Foreign Affairs of Sri Lanka|Foreign Minister]] instead of Prime Minister; Samaraweera maintained his other posts.\n\nIn late January 2007, Samaraweera was replaced as Foreign Minister, but remained as Minister of Ports and Aviation.<ref>[http://english.people.com.cn/200701/29/eng20070129_345575.html \"Sri Lankan president reshuffles cabinet\"], Xinhua, January 29, 2007.</ref> On 9 February 2007, he was sacked from the cabinet together with ministers [[Anura Bandaranaike]] and [[Sripathi Sooriyarachchi]] after falling out with the president. He then went on to create a new political party, the SLFP (Mahajana) wing.\n\nIn October 2013, the Matara Magistrate's Court issued a Court order to arrest him and 10 others for their alleged involvement in obstructing a peaceful protest march in Matara by UNP activists, to oust its leader [[Ranil Wickramasinghe]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailynews.lk/local/arrest-mangala-orders-court | title=ARREST MANGALA ORDERS COURT | work=Dailymirror.lk | date=15 Oct 2013 | access-date=16 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016233022/http://www.dailynews.lk/local/arrest-mangala-orders-court | archive-date=16 October 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2015 Samaraweera was again appointed as Minister of Foreign Affairs under newly elected President [[Maithripala Sirisena]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Sri-Lankan-foreign-minister-Mangala-Samaraweera-to-visit-India/articleshow/45865923.cms | title=Sri Lankan foreign minister Mangala Samaraweera to visit India | work=The Times of India | date=13 January 2015 | accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n*[[List of political families in Sri Lanka]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091201023812/http://www.mangalasamaraweera.com/  Mangala Samaraweera's Official Website]\n*[http://www.lankadissent.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1315:mangala-for-de    Mangala for democratic leadership in SLFP]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091226091022/http://sri_lanka.comnat.unesco.org/index.php?intIdCat=103&blnIsCat=1&intIdLang=1 UNESCO Executive Board]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100324204136/http://www.parliament.lk/directory_of_members/ViewMember.do?memID=186 Parliament profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[G. L. Peiris|Gamini L Peiris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Foreign Affairs of Sri Lanka]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ravi Karunanayake]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anura Bandaranaike]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Foreign Affairs of Sri Lanka]]|years=2005-2007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rohitha Bogollagama]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan foreign ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan Telecommunications ministers}}\n{{Members of 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Samaraweera, Mangala}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Theravada Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Saint Martin's School of Art]]\n[[Category:People from Matara]]\n[[Category:Housing ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Posts ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Telecommunication ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[